Bus was late
I don't care, I guess it's something to say
Ride around with the prams out of daycare
Complain, suited crowds block the way
Slip to a seat, right at the back
And watch the clouds bleed to black
And why race?
I'll get home sometime, like yesterday
My pay's been late a couple of days
Don't complain, trade some sleep for some patience
Have a snack and just relax
Your back needs a break

But ‘Not Worth Hiding’ really bares it all. Rather than feeling like an uncomfortable tell-all, Alex’s honesty instead comes off as super-relatable and rewards you across multiple listens.

annotations:
And it’s not worth hiding if it’s happiness
 That could be on your way
It’s not worth hiding and feeling sad if happiness is on the way. Things do get better !
I cried when I found kissing boys wasn’t for me

This line acts as a reference to the persona’s realisation of her sexual orientation, that being that she doesn’t like boys. The sad yet very real struggle to internally accept her orientation as a part of who she is is exemplified in her breakdown over having this revelation.

But holding someone’s hand
 Should never make you feel ashamed
meaning that you shouldn’t feel ashamed of your relation ship or who you love

And it’s not worth dying for the people
 Who don’t smile at your name

This is a reference to people who make fun of transgender individuals who have changed their name to fit their gender identity. She is saying it is not worth spending your time or feeling upset towards people who will not accept you for your identity.
I learnt to drive to school when I was sixteen

This first line sets the scene of the song to being a type of autobiography. Alex stated that she wrote this song:

for 16-year-old Alex and for anyone who’s struggling to let you know that you’re absolutely perfect just the way you are.

If you love them as a daughter
 Could you love them as a son?
This is directed to parents of transgender (in this case FTM) children.

I opened the paper and it left me in shame
 It said, ”These contagious gays aren’t safe
 And you should keep your kids away”

In Australia, there are often fliers, adverts, and news articles from anti-gay groups in the mail, on tv, and in newspapers. Especially during times of debate such as the same-sex marriage vote. This is in reference to Alex seeing these as she grew up, and also the fact that there have been a lot recently.

annotations: Is there still love in your eyes?

The question has changed from ‘how much love is in your eyes’ to ‘is there still love in your eyes’. Something has faded or is fading—changing from a question of quantity to a question of simple existence.

Wait just a second and you’ll see her
 She’s a yellow fish hiding in the waves
 We we’re both looking down and she jumped right out
 And we laughed and we laughed ‘till it helped
This anecdote slides from present tense to past; the narrator remembers this moment so intensely that it feels like it’s happening right now.

You said “Alex I don’t know where I’m going”
 It was dark but a tear was holding on

They know this person so well that even without being able to see it, they can tell they’re on the edge of tears. This line also suggests the reasons for the relationship ending—self-doubt and fear of the future.

If you painted me what colour would you make me?
 Orange purple blue, who am I to you?
 And what do I need to be to make the whole world want me?
 Is it all about remembering or forgetting?

This verse transitions from questions addressed to the person they miss to questions about their identity, and then cycles back to questioning what that person thinks of them. These questions are a mix of ones with concrete answers, and ones that are more subjective… but even the more objective ones are more about the routines and cycles they represent as opposed to an actual literal question. How does love and identity fit into the bigger world we inhabit?

We’re two steps from the bar
 There’s a jumper in my car
 And we can sit there
 ‘Till we’re warm enough

In the literal sense, they’re remembering the times when there were all the pieces there to make a nice night, but in the metaphorical sense, they’re missing when they used to have everything they needed in the relationship to make it work.
